To achieve a seamless "3D Visual Dashboard" that matches your 5-point monorepo structure, we will treat your Unity 
environment as a physical extension of your frontend design system. By aligning the UI Toolkit (UITK) with your React/Web
standards, your dev workflow and the game dashboard will share a single visual language.

1. Unified "Design Language" Monorepo Structure
In a monorepo (using tools like Nx or Turborepo), create a central design library that both your web frontend and Unity project reference.
Shared Assets: Store CSS/USS constants (colors, spacing, typography) in a central libs/design-system.
Asset Pipeline: Use a shared Figma-to-Code pipeline to export SVGs and Sprites into a format both the React Dashboard and Unity Assets folder can ingest.

2. Matching UI/UX: The "Physical" Frontend
To make the 3D dashboard feel identical to your 2D frontend, we leverage Unity’s World Space UI Toolkit:
World Space Rendering: Switch your Unity Panel Settings to World Space. This allows your "Task Orchestrator" to exist as a floating 3D panel within the game scene.
Web-Style Styling (USS): Since UI Toolkit uses USS (Unity Style Sheets)—a subset of CSS—you can copy the exact hex codes, border-radii, and flex-layouts from your 
React project into Unity. Responsive 3D Panels: Set the Panel Settings to Dynamic Scaling. This ensures that when you zoom in on a task in the 3D dashboard, the text
remains as sharp as it is in your web browser.

3. Integrated Dashboard Logic
The transition from a "Project Listing" to a "Task Detail" view must be consistent across the monorepo:
Shared State Mediator: Use a UI Mediator pattern where a central C# controller (or a React-Unity bridge) listens for clicks on task elements.
The "Drill-Down" UX: When a task is selected in the 3D dashboard:
3D Transition: The camera focuses on the 3D task node.
Detail Overlay: A UI Document pop-up appears (styled like your React detail screen) showing the Azure Rootplanner and Commit History.
Real-Time Sync: Data from the BMS-Milestone Hook is pulled via the same API used by your web frontend to show live status updates.

4. Visualizing the 5-Point Core Plan
Your "Project Heartbeat" should be visible in the 3D environment:
Phase Indicators: Use 3D objects (like glowing pillars or color-coded terminal screens) that change color based on the Health Score provided by your BMS.
Agenda Sync: The Microsoft Graph API data (appointments/deadlines) can be rendered as a floating "Schedule Ring" around your 3D project model.
