The standard industry approach to managing design tokens across a monorepo (e.g., React and Unity) is a Build-Time Transformation Pipeline. Instead of a live server 
syncing tokens at runtime, you use a "Single Source of Truth" that compiles into platform-specific assets during your development or build process. 

1. The Standard Workflow (The "Handover")
The industry standard follows a structured flow from design to code: 
Design Tool (Penpot/Figma): Designers define styles as tokens.
Source of Truth (JSON): Tokens are exported as a standardized JSON file (often following the W3C DTCG draft spec).
Version Control: The JSON file is stored in a dedicated directory within your monorepo (e.g., libs/design-system/tokens.json).
Transformation Engine: A tool like Style Dictionary (by Amazon) reads the JSON and transforms it into the formats your platforms need. 

2. Industry-Standard Platform Mapping
Style Dictionary allows you to generate multiple outputs from one JSON file simultaneously: 

For React: Outputs CSS Custom Properties (variables.css), SCSS, or JavaScript/TypeScript objects.
For Unity: Outputs USS (Unity Style Sheets) files or even C# scripts/constants for use in your 3D engine. 

3. Why This Is the "Standard" Way
This approach is preferred over a live-server concept for several reasons:
Interoperability: Standardized formats (like W3C) mean you aren't locked into one design tool.
Performance: No runtime overhead from fetching theme data over the network; styles are local and instant.
Stability: Versioning your tokens in Git ensures that a design change doesn't accidentally "break" production without a proper code review.
Scalability: You can easily add more platforms (iOS, Android) just by adding a new output configuration to Style Dictionary. 

4. Implementation Tools
If you want to move beyond a manual JSON export, professional teams often use automation tools to bridge the design tool and the repo:
Style Dictionary: The core engine for transforming tokens.
Tokens Studio: A popular tool for managing complex token hierarchies and syncing them directly to GitHub.
Locofy.ai: Can help convert Penpot designs directly into React code, including token integration. 

